                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page in dark ink by a 18th or 19th c. hand:<quote xml:lang="sv"> 1734 års Kat. Theol. in folio N<hi rend="super">o</hi> 43</quote>; further down by the same hand: <quote xml:lang="la">Missale Olomucense</quote> (these words have also been written in pencil above the words in ink).</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Post-medieval binding, possibly 16th or 17th century. Redish-brown leather over wooden boards. The boards have beveled edges. 5 pairs of raised bands and endbands Metal catch plates on<locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and one remaining piece of plate on <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, blind stamped: <quote>Missale<sic> olomucensis</sic>
                                    </quote>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 177</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="275" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="220" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="60" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Elaborate tooling in the shape of frames filled with geometric and vegetative ornaments. The tooling seems to have been gilded, but only traces remain. A medalion in the middle of <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, but the motif is no longer visible. On <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> the frames also contain small medalions with human faces.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather covering worn and damaged. Clasps missing. Leather on parts of the cover and spine renovated with new leather. Old library signa removed from spine and attached to <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100212">Olomouc</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1401">15th century</origDate>. The presense of the patron saints of Olomouc together with the glossing in Czech indicates Olomouc as the place of origin.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript was most likely taken from Olomouc and brought to Sweden as spoils of war during the Thirty Years’ War. It is believed to be the manuscript listed as <quote>Missale Charta</quote> in Vossius’s catalogue of 1651 (U 202:1, p. 68). On <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/> there are three notes glued to the margin. These were orginally attached to the spine. Two of these notes contain signa, the first that of Hammarsköld's catalogue from the 19th century (U 133): <quote>e. 30. 5. 2.</quote>; the second the signum from the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e): <quote>43? Missale</quote> (listed in the catalogue as <quote>Theol. in fol. 43</quote>). The only signum on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> is the current signum <quote>A 177</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
